RBAC - Role-Based Access Control

Simple Meaning
RBAC gives access based on what role a person has in the organization.

Real world example:

Manager can only see his own team
HR can only manage salary
Engineer can only access code repositories

Same in Kubernetes: You define roles and decide which user can do what.

Basic RBAC Example

Role	    Allowed Action	        Resource
Developer	Create and Update	    Pods
Admin	    Create and Delete	    All Resources
Viewer	    Read Only	            All Resources

Four Main RBAC Objects
Object	            Purpose
Role	            Defines permissions inside one namespace
RoleBinding	        Connects a Role to a user
ClusterRole	Defines permissions across whole cluster
ClusterRoleBinding	Connects ClusterRole to a user

Example Role
This Role allows the user to only get, watch, and list pods in the default namespace. No create, no update, no delete.

Rules:
apiGroups: empty means core group
resources: pods
verbs: get, watch, list

Real Benefit for IT Working
Least privilege principle: Users get only what they need
Easy to audit: You can see exactly who has which permissions
Scalable: Create a Role once, bind many users to it
Standard: Most Kubernetes clusters use RBAC as default

